04230nam a22006375i 9780748636747DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20222008stk    fo  d z      eng d  a97807486367477 a10.1515/97807486367472doi  a(DE-B1597)614540  a(OCoLC)1302166069  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  astkcGB-SCT 7aLIT0000002bisacsh1 aNewton, K. M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aModern Literature and the Tragic /cK. M. Newton. 1aEdinburgh : bEdinburgh University Press, c[2022] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (192 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgements -- tIntroduction -- t1. Ibsen’s Ghosts and the Rejection of the Tragic -- t2. Anti-Tragic Drama after Ibsen -- t3. Chekhov and the Tragic -- t4. The Return of the Tragic in Fiction -- t5. Nietzsche and the Redefining of the Tragic -- t6. The ‘Tragico-Dionysian’ and D. H. Lawrence -- t7. The Theatre of the Absurd and the Tragic -- t8. The Tragic, Pragmatism and the Postmodern -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aGBS_insertPreviewButtonPopup('ISBN:9780748636730');This book explores modern literature's responses to the tragic. It examines writers from the latter half of the nineteenth century through to the later twentieth century who respond to ideas about tragedy.Although Ibsen has been accused of being responsible for the 'death of tragedy', Ken Newton argues that Ibsen instead generates an anti-tragic perspective that had a major influence on dramatists such as Shaw and Brecht. By contrast, writers such as Hardy and Conrad, influenced by Schopenhauerean pessimism and Darwinism, attempt to modernise the concept of the tragic. Nietzsche's revisionist interpretation of the tragic influenced writers who either take pessimism or the 'Dionysian' commitment to life to an extreme, as in Strindberg and D. H. Lawrence. Different views emerge in the period following the second world war with the 'Theatre of the Absurd' and postmodern anti-foundationalism.Key FeaturesBroad coverage of drama and fiction by British, European, and American writers Provides readings of particular texts including Tolstoy's Anna Karenina, Ibsen's Ghosts, Strindberg's Miss Julie, Brecht's Mother Courage, Chekhov's Three Sisters, Thomas Hardy's Tess of the d'Urbervilles and Jude the Obscure, Shaw's Saint Joan, Miller's Death of a Salesman, Conrad's Heart of Darkness, and D H Lawrence's The Rainbow and Women in LoveCombines literary interpretation with philosophical discussion, e.g. of Schopenhauer, Nietzsche, Derrida, Rorty"  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000z97831107804680 cprintz978074863673040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780748636747?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780748636747423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780748636747/original  a978-3-11-078046-8  Edinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK